  "ollama_insights": "**Finding:** A staggering 65.4% of campaign spending went towards \"attack ads,\" with $542 million allocated to just these advertisements, compared to $286 million for support ads.\n\n**Implication:** This disproportionate allocation of funds to attack ads has the potential to undermine democracy by creating a culture of fear and division among voters, rather than encouraging constructive debate and civic engagement. As one analyst noted, \"The disproportionate use of attack ads is a recipe for erosion of trust in our democratic institutions.\"\n\nThis finding is particularly alarming given that these attack ads were largely funded by anonymous donors, who spent over $23 billion in the 2024 election cycle. The concentration of this spending in just a handful of districts raises questions about the unequal influence wielded by wealthy donors and the potential for voter disenfranchisement.\n\nAs the country continues to grapple with issues of campaign finance reform and the impact of dark money on our democracy, it is essential that we examine the tactics used by special interest groups to shape public discourse."
